      </a>
      <a class="ribbon-stage" href="#stage-4">
        <div class="ribbon-num">4</div>
        <div class="ribbon-label">Treatment</div>
        <div class="ribbon-substage">the surveillance itself</div>
      </a>
      <a class="ribbon-stage" href="#stage-5">
        <div class="ribbon-num">5</div>
        <div class="ribbon-label">Long-term optimisation</div>
        <div class="ribbon-substage">the surveillance that keeps him in surveillance</div>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- FRAMING -->
  <div class="framing">
    <div class="framing-grid">
      <div class="framing-tile">
        <div class="framing-tile-eyebrow">The patient North Star</div>
        <div class="framing-tile-h">His consultant still holds the cohort. The quarterly visit just does not need to be in clinic.</div>
        <div class="framing-tile-body">Mark trusts Adam. The active-surveillance cohort works because the clinician is reading the trend. <strong>The home pathway preserves the clinical role and removes the clinic visit that did nothing but draw the blood.</strong></div>
      </div>
      <div class="framing-tile">
        <div class="framing-tile-eyebrow">Why this works for him</div>
        <div class="framing-tile-h">Travel saved. Half-days saved. The same surveillance, on time.</div>
        <div class="framing-tile-body">Mark has worked through it, taken his kids to school, looked after a parent. The hospital is an hour&apos;s drive. The clinic visit was always the friction; the blood result was always the point. <strong>The kit moves the friction; the clinical decision-making stays exactly where it was.</strong></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- STAGES -->
  <div class="stages">

    <!-- STAGE 1 -->
    <div class="stage" id="stage-1">
      <div class="stage-side"><div class="stage-number">01</div></div>
      <div class="stage-main">
        <div class="stage-eyebrow">Stratification — the cohort eligible for active surveillance</div>
        <h2 class="stage-title">More than 64,000 men a year are diagnosed with prostate cancer in the UK. Around 6,500 a year choose active surveillance; up to 5,000 more could. Mark sits in that cohort: low-risk disease, watch-and-wait, quarterly PSA. The surveillance is the treatment. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="mark-s1"></span></h2>

        <div class="stage-image" style="padding:0;border:none;background:none;margin-bottom:22px;"><img src="Assets/Mark Story/mark-stage1.png" alt="Mark Stage 1" style="width:100%;height:auto;border-radius:12px;display:block;box-shadow:0 8px 24px rgba(0,32,64,0.12);"></div>

        <div class="pull-quote">
          <p class="pull-quote-text">I am sixty-five and I have prostate cancer. They told me it is the kind that does not need treating, just watching. That is the bit nobody warns you about — what the watching actually costs.</p>
          <div class="pull-quote-attribution">Mark</div>
        </div>

        <div class="whats-happening">
          <div class="whats-happening-label">What is happening</div>
          <div class="whats-happening-body">NICE NG131 sets the framework for active surveillance in low-risk prostate cancer: regular PSA, MRI at intervals, repeat biopsy as triggered by trend. The cohort is well-defined. The challenge is holding the cohort in surveillance without burning the clinic.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="old-way">
          <div class="old-way-label">The old way</div>
          <div class="old-way-body">An expanding AS cohort funnelled through fixed clinic capacity. Patients drop out, present later, get treated harder.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="careteam">
          <div class="careteam-icon">&#x1F465;</div>
          <div class="careteam-body">
            <div class="careteam-label">Who is in the loop</div>
            <div class="careteam-text">Adam, consultant urologist. The MDT. Catherine on the Trust commissioner side. Mark.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="crosslinks">
          <div class="crosslinks-label">Where this lives in the model</div>
          <div class="crosslinks-row">
            <span class="crosslinks-tag">Who</span>
            <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Persona Mark.html" target="_blank">Mark persona</a>
            <span class="crosslinks-tag">Who</span>
            <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Persona Adam.html" target="_blank">Adam persona</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- STAGE 2 -->
    <div class="stage" id="stage-2">
      <div class="stage-side"><div class="stage-number">02</div></div>
      <div class="stage-main">
        <div class="stage-eyebrow">Identification — Adam&apos;s clinic shortlists him</div>
        <h2 class="stage-title">Adam reviews the cohort. Mark fits the profile for the first wave of home PSA: stable trend, comfortable with the kit idea, no clinical concerns. The shortlist of first patients is small and chosen carefully. Mark gets the conversation at the next clinic. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="mark-s2"></span></h2>

        <div class="stage-image" style="padding:0;border:none;background:none;margin-bottom:22px;"><img src="Assets/Mark Story/mark-stage2.png" alt="Mark Stage 2" style="width:100%;height:auto;border-radius:12px;display:block;box-shadow:0 8px 24px rgba(0,32,64,0.12);"></div>

        <div class="pull-quote">
          <p class="pull-quote-text">Adam asked me whether I would be comfortable doing the next PSA at home. I said yes before he had finished the sentence.</p>
          <div class="pull-quote-attribution">Mark</div>
        </div>

        <div class="whats-happening">
          <div class="whats-happening-label">What is happening</div>
          <div class="whats-happening-body">The first patients are picked by the consultant, in clinic, with consent and clinical judgement. The cohort is bounded carefully. The conversation is short because the model preserves the clinical role.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="old-way">
          <div class="old-way-label">The old way</div>
          <div class="old-way-body">Bring everyone in for everything, because there is no other model on offer. The cohort is held by clinic capacity, not clinical judgement.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="careteam">
          <div class="careteam-icon">&#x1F465;</div>
          <div class="careteam-body">
            <div class="careteam-label">Who is in the loop</div>
            <div class="careteam-text">Adam. Clinical nurse specialist. Mark.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="crosslinks">
          <div class="crosslinks-label">Where this lives in the model</div>
          <div class="crosslinks-row">
            <span class="crosslinks-tag">How</span>
            <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Operational.html" target="_blank">Lane 3 — clinician-initiated</a>
            <span class="crosslinks-tag">H&amp;M</span>
            <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Adam Journey.html" target="_blank">Adam&apos;s journey</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- STAGE 3 -->
    <div class="stage" id="stage-3">
      <div class="stage-side"><div class="stage-number">03</div></div>
      <div class="stage-main">
        <div class="stage-eyebrow">Diagnosis — kit out, sample back, result to the consultant first</div>
        <h2 class="stage-title">The kit arrives. Mark takes the sample at home on the day the clinic would have happened. The lab processes it. The result lands in Adam&apos;s system before the next clinic, in trend, with the threshold-alert logic wired in. Mark sees the result only after Adam has read it. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="mark-s3"></span></h2>

        <div class="stage-image" style="padding:0;border:none;background:none;margin-bottom:22px;"><img src="Assets/Mark Story/mark-stage3.png" alt="Mark Stage 3" style="width:100%;height:auto;border-radius:12px;display:block;box-shadow:0 8px 24px rgba(0,32,64,0.12);"></div>

        <div class="pull-quote">
          <p class="pull-quote-text">The kit came in the post. I did it on the Saturday morning. By the following Tuesday I knew Adam had seen the result. Same answer I would have got at the hospital. None of the driving.</p>
          <div class="pull-quote-attribution">Mark</div>
        </div>

        <div class="whats-happening">
          <div class="whats-happening-label">What is happening</div>
          <div class="whats-happening-body">1.25 billion NHS pathology test requests per year, growing ~5.5% annually. Home capillary PSA is the same biochemical assay run on the same lab platform. The clinical interpretation is preserved.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="old-way">
          <div class="old-way-label">The old way</div>
          <div class="old-way-body">Two trips to the hospital — phlebotomy for the blood, second trip for the result. Or, on a bad cycle, a missed appointment and a quietly delayed surveillance round.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="careteam">
          <div class="careteam-icon">&#x1F465;</div>
          <div class="careteam-body">
            <div class="careteam-label">Who is in the loop</div>
            <div class="careteam-text">The supplier shipping the kit. UKAS-accredited lab. Platform writing the result back to the Trust EPR. Adam reading the trend.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="crosslinks">
          <div class="crosslinks-label">Where this lives in the model</div>
